Q4: What is the difference between <ul> and <ol>? Give a real-world example of when you would use each one. Also explain why navigation menus use type="none" instead of just deleting the ul tag.

Answer:
<ul> (Unordered List) displays items with bullet points where the order does not matter.
Example: Navigation menu, shopping list.

<ol> (Ordered List) displays items with numbers where the order matters.
Example: Recipe steps, rankings, instructions.

Navigation menus use type="none" (or CSS list-style:none) instead of deleting the <ul> because the list structure helps accessibility and keeps the HTML semantic while only hiding the bullets.


Q5: What is the difference between <th> and <td>? Why use <th> instead of making <td> bold with CSS? What does a screen reader do differently with each?

Answer:
<th> is a table header cell.
<td> is a normal table data cell.

Using <th> gives semantic meaning to the table structure.
Making <td> bold with CSS only changes appearance, not meaning.

Screen readers recognize <th> as a header and announce it to help users understand the table.
<td> is read as regular table data.



Q6: What is the difference between method="GET" and method="POST"? Why should you never use GET for a login form? Include an example URL showing what GET looks like in the browser address bar.

Answer:
GET sends form data in the URL.
Example:
https://example.com/login?username=raj&password=123

POST sends form data in the request body.

GET should not be used for login forms because usernames and passwords become visible in the URL, browser history, and server logs.

POST is safer because the data is not shown in the address bar.
